anticism that paradoxically made him a global literary icon; the country’s violent end to the twentieth century when its largest economic export was narcotics; and the contemporary period in which a new major author has emerged to create a “literature of national reconstitution.” Harkening back to the Regeneration movement and extending through the early twenty-first century, this book analyzes the cultural implications of Colombia’s relationship to the wider world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aColombian fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aColombian fictiony21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature and globalizationzColombia. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aGlobalization, Gabriel Garcia Marquez, Juan Gabriel Vasquez, Narco-literature, Regeneration movement, Colombia, Colombian culture, Colombian literature.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076647940uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/9781684483693?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781684483693423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781684483693/original  a978-3-11-076647-9  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK